Built in secret types.

A secret's type field is a hint about what is inside. For most types the cluster does not enforce the schema. It is documentation that some controllers check for. Let us go through the common ones.

Opaque is the default. It is just arbitrary key value data, and it covers most user secrets.

The service account token type holds a json web token for a service account. These are auto created per service account and injected into pods.

There are two image pull types. The legacy docker config format, and the modern docker config json format. Both carry registry credentials for pulling private images.

There are convention based types for basic authentication, with a username and password, and for ess-ess-h authentication, with a private key. The cluster does not enforce these, but tools expect those key names.

The tee-el-ess type holds a certificate and a key, under the keys tee-el-ess dot c-r-t and tee-el-ess dot key. It is consumed by ingress resources and by any pod that needs to serve h-t-t-p-s.

And there is a bootstrap token type, used during cluster join with kube-ay-dee-m.

The two you will create most often are tee-el-ess secrets and image pull secrets. A tee-el-ess secret is created most easily with kubectl create secret tls, and it is what an ingress references to terminate h-t-t-p-s. Image pull secrets are next.
